<dl id="n33271b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33271b">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33271b"> 271(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> blind as a batflea <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n33271b"><li>FW 417.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/lexpC.htm#n33271b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/l39pC.htm#n33271b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n33271b">MS Gilvarry-22</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pCd3" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pCd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pC/pCd3.htm#n33271b">Draft: III&sect;1C.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>All bat-fleas are blind</mark>. This absence of eyes, in fleas which are parasites of strictly nocturnal animals, lends colour to the suggestion that fleas which are blind have lost their eyes because they had no need of them. Disuse is speedily followed by degeneration. <small> Harold Russell, <a name="HRTF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HRTF"><cite title="source">The Flea</cite></a> (1913) 107</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Phrase, blind as a bat. Butterfly; flea. </mm> </dd></dl>
